<exercise xml:id="laplace-exponential-order">
  <statement>
    <p>
      In your own words, what does it mean for a function to be of 
      <em>exponential order</em>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      A function <m>f(t)</m> is of exponential order if, for large <m>t</m>, 
      it does not grow faster than some exponential <m>e^{\alpha t}</m>.  
      More precisely, there exist constants <m>M,\alpha</m> such that 
      <m>|f(t)| \le M e^{\alpha t}</m> for all sufficiently large <m>t</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      This ensures that the Laplace integral will converge for <m>s &gt; \alpha</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="laplace-transform-of-1">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Suppose <m>f(t) \equiv 1</m> on <m>[0,\infty)</m>.  
      Compute <m>{\cal L}[f(t)]</m>.  
      What is the domain of <m>F(s)</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Compute directly:
    </p>
    <me>
      {\cal L}[1](s)
      = \int_{0}^{\infty} e^{-st} dt
      = \left[ -\frac{1}{s} e^{-st} \right]_{0}^{\infty}
      = \frac{1}{s}.
    </me>

    <p>
      This converges only if <m>s > 0</m>.  
      Thus:
    </p>
    <me>
      F(s) = \frac{1}{s}, \qquad s > 0.
    </me>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="laplace-transform-exp-at">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Suppose <m>f(t)=e^{at}</m> on <m>[0,\infty)</m>.  
      Compute <m>{\cal L}[f(t)]</m>.  
      What is the domain of <m>F(s)</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Compute:
    </p>
    <md>
      <mrow> {\cal L}[e^{at}]s
      \amp = \int_0^\infty e^{-st} e^{at}\, dt </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = \int_0^\infty e^{-(s-a)t}\, dt </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{s-a}, </mrow>
    </md>
    <p>
      which converges if <m>s-a &gt; 0</m>, i.e. <m>s &gt; a</m>.  
      Thus:
    </p>
    <me>
      F(s) = \frac{1}{s-a}, \qquad s &gt; a.
    </me>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="unit-step-laplace">
  <statement>
    <p>
      The <alert>unit step function</alert> is
    </p>
    <me>
      u(t) =
      \begin{cases}
         0 \amp t &lt; 0,\\[4pt]
         1 \amp t\ge 0.
      \end{cases}
    </me>

    <ol marker="(a)">
      <li><p>Graph <m>u(t)</m>.</p></li>

      <li><p>Define <m>u_a(t)=u(t-a)</m>.  
             Write it as a piecewise function and graph it.</p></li>

      <li><p>Compute <m>{\cal L}[u_a(t)]</m>.</p></li>
    </ol>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <ol marker="(a)">
      <li>
        <p>
          Graph: zero for <m>t &lt; 0</m>, one for <m>t\ge0</m>.  
          A correct sketch shows a step jump at <m>t=0</m>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Since <m>u_a(t)=u(t-a)</m>,
        </p>
        <me>
          u_a(t) =
          \begin{cases}
            0 \amp t &lt; a,\\[4pt]
            1 \amp t\ge a.
          \end{cases}
        </me>
        <p>
          The graph is a horizontal zero line until <m>t=a</m>, then jumps to 1.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Compute:
        </p>
        <md>
          <mrow> {\cal L}[u_a(t)]
          \amp = \int_a^\infty e^{-st} dt </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = \frac{e^{-as}}{s},
          \qquad s &gt; 0. </mrow>
        </md>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="inverse-laplace-1">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Compute the inverse Laplace transform of
    </p>
    <me>
      F(s) = \frac{2s-3}{(s-3)(s+2)}.
    </me>
    <p>
      Use partial fractions and tables.  
      Does AI agree with your result?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Write:
    </p>
    <me>
      \frac{2s-3}{(s-3)(s+2)} 
      = \frac{A}{s-3} + \frac{B}{s+2}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Solve:
    </p>
    <me>
      2s-3 = A(s+2) + B(s-3).
    </me>

    <p>
      Matching coefficients:
      <br/><m>A+B=2</m>,  
      <br/><m>2A - 3B = -3</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Solve:
    </p>
    <me>
      A=1,\qquad B=1.
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore:
    </p>
    <me>
      F(s) = \frac{1}{s-3} + \frac{1}{s+2}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Inverse Laplace:
    </p>
    <me>
      {\cal L}^{-1}[F] = e^{3t} + e^{-2t}.
    </me>

  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="inverse-laplace-2">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Compute the inverse Laplace transform of
    </p>
    <me>
      F(s) = \frac{3}{(s^{2}+4)(s^{2}+9)}.
    </me>
    <p>
      Use partial fractions and tables.  
      Does AI agree with your result?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Use the identity:
    </p>
    <me>
      \frac{1}{(s^2+a^2)(s^2+b^2)}
      = \frac{1}{b^2-a^2}\!
        \left( \frac{1}{s^2+a^2} - \frac{1}{s^2+b^2} \right).
    </me>

    <p>
      Here <m>a=2</m>, <m>b=3</m>, so <m>b^2-a^2 = 9-4 = 5</m>.
    </p>

    <md>
      <mrow> F(s)
      \amp = 3\cdot \frac{1}{5}
        \left( \frac{1}{s^2+4} - \frac{1}{s^2+9} \right) </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = \frac{3}{5}\frac{1}{s^2+4}
        - \frac{3}{5}\frac{1}{s^2+9}. </mrow>
    </md>

    <p>Inverse Laplace:</p>

    <me>
      {\cal L}^{-1}[1/(s^2+4)] = \frac{1}{2}\sin(2t),\\
      {\cal L}^{-1}[1/(s^2+9)] = \frac{1}{3}\sin(3t).
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore:
    </p>

    <md>
      <mrow> {\cal L}^{-1}[F]
      \amp = \frac{3}{5}\cdot \frac{1}{2}\sin(2t)
        - \frac{3}{5}\cdot \frac{1}{3}\sin(3t) </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = \frac{3}{10}\sin(2t)
        - \frac{1}{5}\sin(3t). </mrow>
    </md>

  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="laplace-of-piecewise-f">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Use the definition of Laplace transform to compute <m>{\cal L}[f(t)](s)</m> 
      for the function <m>f(t)</m> graphed in <xref ref="GraphLaplaceTransformA"/>.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="GraphLaplaceTransformA">
    <caption>Function <m>f(t)</m>.</caption>
    <image width="35%">
      <description>A graph of a piecewise function f(t). For t less than 1, the function 
        equals 0, shown by a horizontal line on the t-axis with a filled dot at t = 0 and an 
        open circle at t = 1. For t greater than or equal to 1, the function increases linearly, 
        passing through the points (1, 1) and (2, 2), and continues upward with an arrow.
      </description>
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}
           \draw [black!60,line width=0.3pt,-latex] (-1,0) -- (3,0) node [below] at (2.75,0) {$t$};
           \draw [black!60,line width=0.3pt,-latex] (0,-1) -- (0,3) node [left] at (0,2.75) {$f(t)$};
          \draw [linecolor,line width=2pt] (0,0) -- (1,0); 
          \draw [linecolor,line width=2pt,-latex] (1,1) -- (2.75,2.75); 
   \fill [linecolor] (0,0) circle (3pt);
\fill [linecolor] (1,1) circle (3pt);
\fill [linecolor] (2,2) circle (3pt) node [right] at (2.3,2,1) {$(2,2)$};
\draw [linecolor] (1,0) circle (3pt);
\foreach \x/\xtext in {1/1, 2/2}
    \draw[shift={(\x,0)}] (0pt,2pt) -- (0pt,-2pt) node[below] {$\xtext$};
\foreach \y/\ytext in {1/1, 2/2}
    \draw[shift={(0,\y)}] (-2pt,0pt) -- (2pt,0pt) node[left] {$\ytext$};
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>
   </figure>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      From the graph:
    </p>
    <me>
      f(t)=
      \begin{cases}
        0, \amp 0\le t &lt; 1,\\
        t, \amp t\ge 1.
      \end{cases}
    </me>

    <p>
      Then:
    </p>
    <md>
      <mrow> {\cal L}[f(t)](s)
      \amp = \int_{0}^{1} 0\cdot e^{-st}dt
        + \int_{1}^{\infty} t e^{-st} dt </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = \int_{1}^{\infty} t e^{-st} dt. </mrow>
    </md>

    <p>
      Compute using integration by parts (or a table):
    </p>
    <me>
      \int t e^{-st}dt
      = -\frac{t}{s}e^{-st} - \frac{1}{s^2}e^{-st}.
    </me>

    <p>Evaluate from 1 to <m>\infty</m>:</p>

    <me>
      {\cal L}[f(t)](s)
      = \left[ -\frac{t}{s}e^{-st} - \frac{1}{s^2}e^{-st} \right]_{1}^{\infty}
      = \frac{1}{s}e^{-s} + \frac{1}{s^2}e^{-s}.
    </me>

    <p>
      So:
    </p>
    <me>
      {\cal L}[f(t)](s) = e^{-s}\left(\frac{1}{s} + \frac{1}{s^{2}}\right),\qquad s &gt; 0.
    </me>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="laplace-of-piecewise-g">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Use the definition of Laplace transform to compute <m>{\cal L}[g(t)](s)</m> 
      for the function <m>g(t)</m> graphed in <xref ref="GraphLaplaceTransformB"/>.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="GraphLaplaceTransformB">
    <caption>Function <m>g(t)</m>.</caption>
    <image width="35%">
      <description>A graph of a piecewise function g(t). Along the t‑axis, the function is 0 
        from the origin up to t=a, shown by a horizontal line with a filled dot at t=0 
        and an open circle at t=a. From t=a to t=b, the function jumps to a 
        constant value c, represented by a horizontal line at height c, with a filled dot 
        at t=a and an open circle at t=b. For t greater than b, the function returns to 0, 
        indicated by a horizontal line on the t‑axis starting at a filled dot at t=b and 
        extending to the right with an arrow.
      </description>
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}
            \draw [black!60,line width=0.3pt,-latex] (-1,0) -- (3,0) node [below] at (2.75,0) {$t$};
   \draw [black!60,line width=0.3pt,-latex] (0,-1) -- (0,3) node [left] at (0,2.75) {$g(t)$};
   \draw [linecolor,line width=2pt] (0,0) -- (0.9,0); 
   \draw [linecolor,line width=2pt] (1,1) -- (1.9,1); 
   \draw [linecolor,line width=2pt,-latex] (2,0) -- (3,0); 
   \fill [linecolor] (0,0) circle (3pt);
\fill [linecolor] (1,1) circle (3pt);
\draw [linecolor] (2,1) circle (3pt);
\fill [linecolor] (2,0) circle (3pt);
\draw [linecolor] (1,0) circle (3pt);
\foreach \x/\xtext in {1/a, 2/b}
    \draw[shift={(\x,0)}] (0pt,2pt) -- (0pt,-2pt) node[below] {$\xtext$};
\foreach \y/\ytext in {1/c}
    \draw[shift={(0,\y)}] (-2pt,0pt) -- (2pt,0pt) node[left] at (-0.15,0) {$\ytext$};
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>
   </figure>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      From the graph:
    </p>
    <me>
      g(t)=
      \begin{cases}
        0, \amp 0\le t &lt; a,\\
        c, \amp a \le t &lt; b,\\
        0, \amp t \ge b.
      \end{cases}
    </me>

    <p>
      Then:
    </p>
    <md>
      <mrow> {\cal L}[g(t)](s)
      \amp = \int_{a}^{b} c\, e^{-st}\, dt </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = c\left[ -\frac{1}{s}e^{-st} \right]_{a}^{b} </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = \frac{c}{s}\bigl( e^{-as} - e^{-bs}\bigr),
      \quad s &gt; 0. </mrow>
    </md>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="inverse-laplace-3">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Find the inverse Laplace transform of
    </p>
    <me>
      F(s) = \frac{2s}{s^{2}-1}.
    </me>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Factor denominator: <m>s^{2}-1 = (s-1)(s+1)</m>.
      Note:
    </p>

    <md>
      <mrow> \frac{2s}{s^{2}-1}
      \amp = \frac{2s}{(s-1)(s+1)} </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{s-1} + \frac{1}{s+1}. </mrow>
    </md>

    <p>Thus:</p>
    <me>
      {\cal L}^{-1}[F]
      = e^{t} + e^{-t}.
    </me>
  </solution>
</exercise>

</exercises>

</section>

      <section xml:id="sec-Advancedlearningobjectives31">
        <title>Advanced learning objectives</title>

        <p>
          In addition to mastering the basic objectives, here are the tasks you should be able 
          to perform, with practice:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
 Interpret the Laplace transform as moving between time and frequency domains, especially for systems governed by equations like <m>m x'' + c x' + kx = f(t)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
      Analyze why the Laplace method handles discontinuities and piecewise-defined inputs effectively.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
      Apply the Laplace transform framework to understand applications in areas such as signal processing, electrical circuits, and physical modeling.
            </p>
          </li>

        </ul>

      </section>


</handout>